391,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-17 13:14:08+00:00,38900806,aleju/imgaug,11698516,aleju,,,266057490,337227152,"That sounds like you have essentially three different augmentation pipelines? Then you should just define three Sequentials and apply each of them on their own -- no need to wrap them in one big Sequential.

You could also name the Sequentials (`Sequential(..., name=""examplename"")`) and then use three augmentation runs and each time use `hooks` to activate/deactive specific Sequentials. But that seems like a rather convoluted solution.

Btw, you are using static values for all augmenters. E.g. `Affine(rotate=-45)` rotates every image by -45 degrees. You probably want `Affine(rotate=(-45, 45))` (rotate by -45 to 45 degrees) and `Fliplr(0.5)` (flip 50% of all images, `Fliplr()` flips 0% by default).",{},OWNER,User,False
411,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-29 00:52:46+00:00,10074815,berdario/pew,752835,berdario,,,143537791,243010838,"I fixed this. I went in the opposite direction you suggested (that is, `pew rm` is now as strict as `pew wipeenv`).

so, if you'd now want to ignore errors in pew commands in a bash script you could use `|| true` or `|| :` (if you prefer bashisms)

```
pew wipeenv $VENV_NAME || true
pew rm      $VENV_NAME || true
```

Unfortunately this is one of the cases in which a type checker would've helped to avoid forgetting to return the proper error code. In all my new projects I try to use mypy and Python3.5... but unfortunately I cannot be as bold here if I want to keep compatibility with old versions of Python (and type checking without annotation syntax is just ugly)

Thanks for reporting the issue, and sorry for not acting on it earlier.",{},,User,False
