1618,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-04 00:56:06+00:00,54787116,guyzmo/git-repo,254441,guyzmo,,,226148858,299075139,"well, it's already possible, even though the syntax isn't as lean as you'd like it to be!

Here's how:

```shell
git hub add masaeedu/git-repo github/masaeedu/git-repo
 % git hub add masaeedu/git-repo github/masaeedu/git-repo 
Successfully added `masaeedu/git-repo` as remote named `github/masaeedu/git-repo`
 % git hub add someotheruser/git-repo github/someotheruser/git-repo
Successfully added `masaeedu/differentlynamedgitrepo` as remote named `github/masaeedu/differentlynamedgitrepo`
 % git bb add bitbucketuser/git-repo-mirror bb/bitbucketuser/git-repo-mirror
Successfully added `bitbucketuser/git-repo-mirror` as remote named `bb/bitbucketuser/git-repo-mirror`
 % git remote
all
bb/bitbucketuser/git-repo-mirror
github
github/masaeedu/differentlynamedgitrepo
github/masaeedu/git-repo
github/someotheruser/git-repo
```

the syntax is a bit more verbose, though you could make a shell function (or a git alias) like:

```shell
% function git-better-add() { git $1 add $2/$3 }
% git-better-add hub github masaeedu/git-repo
```

if you make it a script in your path (`git-better-add`) you'll be able to call it as `git better-add`. Not as cool as you would like, but still a bit better?",{},,User,False
