2537,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-20 09:29:37+00:00,11974348,evansd/whitenoise,133278,RyanBalfanz,,,88758100,149493022,"@bwarren2 You don't need to include your `bower_components` assets, as @evansd correctly suggests. And Docker seems like super overkill IMO.

Here's what I do, it works really well for me. YMMV.

Use a multi-buildpack in your [app.json](https://devcenter.heroku.com/articles/app-json-schema) so that you can leverage the [https://github.com/apiaryio/heroku-buildpack-nodejs-grunt](https://github.com/apiaryio/heroku-buildpack-nodejs-grunt) buildpack to build your frontend's assets using bower/grunt.

```app.json
	""buildpacks"": [{
		""url"": ""https://github.com/apiaryio/heroku-buildpack-nodejs-grunt""
	}, {
		""url"": ""https://github.com/heroku/heroku-buildpack-python""
	}]
```

In your `package.json` to tell heroku to do a `bower install`, `grunt`, or whatever you need to do by setting your pre/postinstall scripts.
```
  ""scripts"": {
    ""test"": ""echo \""Error: no test specified\"" && exit 1"",
    ""preinstall"": ""bash ./preinstall.sh"",
    ""postinstall"": ""bash ./postinstall.sh""
  },
```

Where, `postinstall.sh` is something like this:

```
#!/bin/bash -ex

echo ""Post-install started""

./node_modules/bower/bin/bower --verbose install
./node_modules/grunt-cli/bin/grunt --verbose build # e.g. concat, uglify, etc.

echo ""Post-install completed""
```

Whatever artifacts you create there should sit in a directory listed in your Django app's `settings.STATICFILES_DIRS`.

Now, so long as you've configured Django's static files correctly to be served from you build artifacts (i.e. your `STATIC_ROOT` via `STATICFILES_DIRS`, you should be good to go. Heroku will run `manage.py collectstatic` for you during the heroku-buildpack-python build phase -- make sure it captures everything bower installed, or anything else you've built with grunt.

Note: You might also want to set `NPM_CONFIG_PRODUCTION= false` to install any `devDependencies` declared in your package.json rather then polluting your `dependencies` and relying on the default value.",{},,User,False
