2954,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-01 18:52:42+00:00,99481053,ahopkins/sanic-jwt,1540275,vltr,,,289345262,362365097,"> It screams microservices. Looking back now, it was probably a mistake to omit the application to just blueprints.

Well, yes or no. Sanic is flexible, as is Flask, bottle, web2py, klein, japronto ... You can start from a simple hello world route or end up with a complex stack, it all depends on your specific need. I find this model attractive since I can scale it up without any hidden black magic behind it (or the need to read source code to understand why it doesn't).

>  Or, perhaps we extract all the settings out into a new super class that can be instantiated on either `Sanic` or `Blueprint`.

This put a smile on my face :smile: Since a config class can be inherited for granularity, things can be even easier to setup, ex:

```python
class MyJwtConfig(sanic_jwt.Config):
    SECRET = 'abracadavra'
    OPTION1 = False

class MyJwtForBP(MyJwtConfig):
    OPTION1 = True

initialize(app, config=MyJwtConfig())
# or
initialize(custom_bp, config=MyJwtForBP())
```

Does it makes sense?",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
