3929,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-18 17:46:14+00:00,23816128,ecordell/pymacaroons,66491,rogpeppe,,,257151870,330300577,"> I guess if I needed to sum up my position on this: binding to both the root and the parent is most flexible for users and at least as safe as just binding to the root.

Re-using third party caveat ids is an optimisation. If dischargers avoid that optimisation when adding third party caveats (and I haven't seen any argument as to why the optimisation might be important), then the problem your bind variant is addressing does not exist.

If you have a discharger that does unwisely reuse caveat ids, my understanding of @rescrv's argument is something like this.

Here's my understanding of the flow you're suggesting.

	TS:
		M := new M(k1).addThird(Discharger1, k2)
	TS → Client:
		M
	Client → Discharger1:
		thirdPartyCaveatId(M)
	Discharger1:
		DM1 := new M(k2).addThird(Discharger2, reusedKey)
	Discharger1 → Client:
		DM1
	Client → DischargeService:
		DM1
	DischargeService → Discharger2:
		thirdPartyCaveatId(DM1)
	Discharger2:
		DM2 := new M(reusedKey)
	Discharger2 → DischargeService:
		DM2
	DischargeService:
		DM2' = DM1.bindForRequest(DM2)
	DischargeService → Client
		DM2'
	Client:
		DM1' = M.bindForRequest(DM1)
		DM2'' = M.bindForRequest(DM2')
	Client → TS:
		M, DM1', DM2''

Objective: client wants to be to reuse DM2 for another macaroon.

Note: DischargeService cannot necessarily know what the target
service is. That is, it's possible that TS is also Client.

So, to reuse DM2 for another macaroon, Client also acts as
TS and goes through the above steps until it has acquired DM1.
Then it can trivially obtain reusedKey because it is privy
to M's root key.

Since it knows reusedKey, it can now reuse DM2 by computing
the signature of DM2 starting from reusedKey, giving it the
unbound version of DM2, which it can then use to discharge
any new third party caveat added by Discharger1 that reuses the
same root key.
",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
