4507,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-02 16:11:02+00:00,24561828,gunthercox/ChatterBot,2030578,gunthercox,,,274386807,348701849,"@tisuchi If you are using Django, then it is possible to specify your own table names as a part of the model meta data attributes. There is a section describing it in the Django documentation:

https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.11/ref/models/options/#db-table

ChatterBot has abstract base classes for each model available that you can import and use to create new models that have an modified model name.

I'll note that this isn't something I've tried before, I'm purely going off of what appears to be possible based on the Django docs.

Here is a quick example of what your modified models might look like:

```python
# models.py

from chatterbot.ext.django_chatterbot.abstract_models import AbstractBaseStatement

class CustomStatement(AbstractBaseStatement):

    class Meta:
        db_table = 'my_custom_table_name'
```

```python
# settings.py

CHATTERBOT = {
    'statement_model': 'CustomStatement'
}
```

I haven't tested the code above, but hopefully it might guide you in the right direction.
You _might_ end up needing to create your own, new models for ALL of ChatterBot's abstract base models for this to work. If this is the case then you'll probably have to set `CHATTERBOT['django_app_name']` equal to whatever your Django App is called in your `settings.py` file.",{},OWNER,User,False
