4962,IssueCommentEvent,2016-01-27 15:01:49+00:00,35341934,svenkreiss/pysparkling,2775078,svenkreiss,,,129159373,175670800,"Hmm, I can reproduce your error, but I can fix it with `pip install doctest-ignore-unicode`. Then `nosetests` runs fine. 

Don't run `python setup.py test`. If you want to run through `setup.py`, run `python setup.py nosetests`.",{},,User,False
4964,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-12 13:13:33+00:00,35341934,svenkreiss/pysparkling,2775078,svenkreiss,,,110952087,147395196,"Thanks for the PR. Looks great!

Doctests get confused with the unicode literal and this is a problem that has been bugging me for a while with other tests as well. That's why I avoided to use any strings in doctests (which is also weird). I just found this workaround and I am going to try this: https://github.com/gnublade/doctest-ignore-unicode

I should probably add to the README, that `python setup.py test` does not run the doctests but `nosetests` does. Sorry.",{},,User,False
4975,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-22 14:32:57+00:00,47729070,tk0miya/testing.mysqld,22371,dsully,,,342842101,406871018,"Yes, if self.mysql_install_db is None, then on line 52 find_program() will raise a RuntimeError.

Additionally, on line 123, the os.path.islink() will try to check against None.",{},NONE,User,False
4976,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-11 02:27:38+00:00,32899829,trevorstephens/gplearn,5210848,trevorstephens,,,273107892,343633823,Fixes #50 ,{},OWNER,User,False
4978,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-14 06:05:47+00:00,32899829,trevorstephens/gplearn,5210848,trevorstephens,,,331964300,397181540,"Unfortunately `gplearn` does not yet implement any classification estimator. It's slated for the next release but I need to find a lot of time to get it done properly. SymbolicRegressor out of the box is strictly for regression problems.

You might be able to hack it using custom fitness measures, AND also transforming any output. All while remembering that your `y` is binary, but `y_pred` out of the regressor is a float. Perhaps a transform of `y_pred`: stardardising and then passing through a sigmoid/logit function might be a solution. 

It is something that I've been pondering but have not yet come up with a good robust solution for. Most of the literature simply jumps straight into the classification (most literature uses positive regression = 1, negative = 0) without addressing probabilities or something useful like that. A bit of a disconnect between ML and GP that is one of the things that `gplearn` aims to address.",{},OWNER,User,False
4983,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-20 13:43:21+00:00,120225562,vn-ki/anime-downloader,31964688,vn-ki,,,334056402,398752986,"@WhoPunkedU I have released anime-downloader 2.6.1 which should fix that issue.
Update with
```
pip install -U anime-downloader[cloudflare]
```",{},OWNER,User,False
