5732,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-07 16:28:14+00:00,8272640,kvesteri/sqlalchemy-utils,753919,mehcode,,,110099362,146252997,"From what I understand we do it this way so that `encrypt(""b"") == encrypt(""b"")` to allow for queryability of encrypted values. There is the https://github.com/kvesteri/sqlalchemy-utils/blob/master/sqlalchemy_utils/types/encrypted.py#L94 which uses (from the documentation):

 - AES in CBC mode with a 128-bit key for encryption; using PKCS7 padding.
 - HMAC using SHA256 for authentication.
 - Initialization vectors are generated using os.urandom().

---

If you're suggesting that the Fernet engine be the default I'd honestly be fine with that as long as we push it out as a minor version bump.",{},,User,False
5735,IssueCommentEvent,2015-01-16 07:34:41+00:00,8272640,kvesteri/sqlalchemy-utils,398714,kvesteri,,,54530489,70217766,"I've had the same problem as you (having to type default=uuid.uuid4 all over the place). However I think this is not the way to go for the following reasons:
* This is PostgreSQL specific
* What if user wants to use uuid-ossp for PostgreSQL (see http://stackoverflow.com/a/13146662)? 
* What if user wants to override the default?

I think the best way to implement would be to introduce some kind of type rule system. The rules would be implemented using listeners.
```
@type_rule(UUIDType)
def process_uuid(column):
    if column.default is None:
        column.default = uuid.uuid4
```",{},,User,False
