6123,IssueCommentEvent,2017-12-17 17:51:13+00:00,2062577,josiahcarlson/parse-crontab,209346,josiahcarlson,,,276030577,352272929,"I think they are weird by judgement of what I expect libraries to do. And *I* have messed up ranges where I wanted `5-8` and accidentally wrote `8-5`. Typos happen. And the range syntax as proposed, and as implemented by cron, violates at least 4 Python zens (as I interpret them):
```
Explicit is better than implicit.
Errors should never pass silently.
Unless explicitly silenced.
In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess.
```

In this case, errors are being passed silently for the sake of the support of a somewhat ambiguous looping range semantic. And at least in the case here, a bigger Go library has the same behavior, for a collection of reasons I am not party to, but which I suspect overlap with my own reasons - given that our algorithms are fundamentally the same (seriously, read their library).

When I've got time over the holidays, I'll make a syntax available so you can do this unambiguously, like say `loop=False/True`, defaulting to False and raising an exception. Could you describe an unambiguous behavior, and/or offer a patch? Or do you just want the feature and are just voting?",{},OWNER,User,False
