6427,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-30 22:59:26+00:00,4025652,invisibleroads/socketIO-client,798568,scfc,,,81617590,107097962,"With regard to motivation, in our cluster ([Wikimedia Tools](https://wikitech.wikimedia.org/wiki/Nova_Resource:Tools)) a homebrewed backport of requests 2.0.0 is installed on Precise instances (and it does offer `response.content`, but see below).  However, my backport of socketIO_client is intended for the ""general audience"", i. e. all Precise instances in existence.  Requiring them to update to requests 2.0.0 to install socketIO_client is not an option because too many things could break (described in many more words at https://wiki.ubuntu.com/StableReleaseUpdates).  So I need to make socketIO_client compatible with requests 0.8.2 because that is what will be available.

I have revised my patch, though.  While previously I always used `response.content`, I now use it only if `response.text` is not available à la:

```python
-    response_parts = response.text.split(':')
+    try:
+        response_text = response.text
+    except AttributeError:
+        response_text = response.content
+    response_parts = response_text.split(':')
```

This works with requests 0.8.2 as shipped with Precise and with our 2.0.0 backport.

What I don't know is if the success of my test script is indicative of a universally working solution or `stream.wikimedia.org` is just too ""plain"" so that there are no differences between `response.text` and `response.content` with that particular server.  I mean ""universally working"" here with a grain of salt: If some edge cases do not work, that's okay, but with my backport a user on a Precise machine should be able to successfully work with other servers besides `stream.wikimedia.org` :-).",{},,User,False
6428,IssueCommentEvent,2016-05-06 20:33:48+00:00,4025652,invisibleroads/socketIO-client,5799715,ocschwar,,,153274205,217551258,"And found another, but it belongs in python-engineio, called by flask-socketio: 

in socket.py, 

`    def _websocket_handler(self, ws):
        """"""Engine.IO handler for websocket transport.""""""

        def writer():
            while True:
                try:
                    packets = self.poll()
                except IOError:
                    break
                try:
                    for pkt in packets:
                        ws.send(pkt.encode(always_bytes=False))
                except:
                    break

        self.server.start_background_task(writer)

        if self.connected:
            # the socket was already connected, so this is an upgrade
            print ("" _websocket_handler(self, ws) join:"",self.queue.qsize())

            self.queue.join()  # flush the queue first
            print ("" _websocket_handler(self, ws):"")
`
That join() calls comes BEFORE the call to start_background_task(), which is responsible for emptying the queue. For some reason, Python client calls result in the queue already having a packet to send, while JS client calls do not. ",{},,User,False
