6929,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-09 16:57:39+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,8004078,Roshrini,47359,apache,310665143,379821318,"@HeliWang I tried the example code you provided. 
Seems like in Python you are passing  `for_training=False`
```
mod.bind(for_training=False, data_shapes=[('input_0', random_input.shape)], label_shapes=None)
```
But in Scala, you are not passing `forTraining` parameter
mod.bind(dataShapes = dataDesc)
So, by default its keeping `forTraining = true`

If you set that parameter to false, you will get the same result as python",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
