7423,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-05 18:30:47+00:00,60273704,mozilla/DeepSpeech,14961916,andi4191,131524,mozilla,240443211,313187805,"@tilmankamp : I checked the code from tensor flow API

** if checkpoint_dir:
    all_hooks.append(basic_session_run_hooks.StepCounterHook(
        output_dir=checkpoint_dir, every_n_steps=log_step_count_steps))

    if (save_summaries_steps and save_summaries_steps > 0) or (
        save_summaries_secs and save_summaries_secs > 0):
      all_hooks.append(basic_session_run_hooks.SummarySaverHook(
          scaffold=scaffold,
          save_steps=save_summaries_steps,
          save_secs=save_summaries_secs,
          output_dir=checkpoint_dir))
    if save_checkpoint_secs and save_checkpoint_secs > 0:
      all_hooks.append(basic_session_run_hooks.CheckpointSaverHook(
          checkpoint_dir, save_secs=save_checkpoint_secs, scaffold=scaffold))

  if hooks:
    all_hooks.extend(hooks)
  return MonitoredSession(session_creator=session_creator, hooks=all_hooks,
                          stop_grace_period_secs=stop_grace_period_secs)**

It appears that if checkpoint_dir is mentioned it creates another StepCounterHook which counts steps per seconds whereas if we pass save_checkpoint_secs then it creates another CheckpointSaverHook.

If I just pass the checkpoint_dir and no save_checkpoint_secs in MonitoredTrainingSession it is still resuming the epoch count from there on. I am not really sure how StepCounterHook is influencing the checkpointing alone because from the StepCounterHook code it appears to be dealing with summary alone in all of its member functions.

PS: This issue appears to be a blocker now.",{},,User,False
7425,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-27 08:40:45+00:00,60273704,mozilla/DeepSpeech,12054740,kdavis-mozilla,131524,mozilla,260326965,332451745,"Thanks for the great visualization! It's more than I'd expected to get!

As to the data, we ""whiten"" each clip before it's fed to the network[[1](https://github.com/mozilla/DeepSpeech/blob/master/util/audio.py#L46)]. So you shouldn't need to do any audio preprocessing like normalizing audio inputs.

To debug, I've a few questions:
- Why did you increase the learning rate from 0.0001 to 0.0002? If the learning rate it too, high the model will not converge.
- If you use your data alone with the learning rate 0.0002, does the model converge?
- If you use your data alone with the learning rate 0.0001, does the model converge?
- If you use your data + TED with the learning rate 0.0001, does the model converge?",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
