8017,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-19 23:09:13+00:00,6670942,boto/botocore,2643092,JordonPhillips,327752,boto,126768121,186444226,"In addition to pulling in https://github.com/boto/boto3/issues/220#issuecomment-171477361, #801 should address this issue.

S3 has a concept of virtual addressing and path style addressing. Virtual host style is preferred, but it relies on DNS propagation and so until that has happened, S3 sends a redirect when you make a request on the virtual host. The problem is the way urllib handles different body types. For file-like objects, it will send a packet before the rest of the body. It will then have time to receive the redirect. For raw string or bytes, however, it will send everything in one go. If that results in a big enough body, S3 will close the connection (probably it looks like an attack of some sort). #801 will wrap raw bodies in a file-like object to dance around the issue.

The other half of the issue, pyopenssl, can hopefully be solved by disabling it in our vendored version of requests.",{},,User,False
