8252,IssueCommentEvent,2017-08-31 08:05:03+00:00,62567919,Yubico/yubikey-manager,9592259,dagheyman,531825,Yubico,254038386,326221732,"Ok, first for the troubleshooting of the actual issue. Does installing `python-pyotherside` or `yubico-yubioath-desktop` change anything as suggested in #19 ? These steps might be worth trying as well: https://github.com/Yubico/yubioath-desktop/issues/172#issuecomment-321343125

----

Regarding your questions, I'll try my best to answer them.

> When does the yubikey switch to mode U2F ? From what I understand: U2F
is always possible with every YubiKey. It does not need to be
configured. It is never associated to any slot. It is always available
and cannot be deactivated (if your yubikey hardware supports U2F of
course). Correct ?

U2F functionality is enabled by default in YK4s and currently sold NEOs. You are correct in that it doesn't need any configuration and doesn't effect the two slots. The functionality can be disabled, by disabling the U2F mode. U2F as a transport is also used in this tool for mode switching, when it is the only transport mode available.

Example:
`$ ykman mode u`
will disable OTP and CCID, and only leave U2F enabled.
`$ ykman mode u+o+c`
will then enable all modes again, using the U2F transport.

> CCID:
Is it correct to state: Whenever I enable mode CCID (with the
corresponding mode bit), the yubikey will be in CCID mode when inserted. ?
Or would there be for instance the possibility to have the CCID mode
enable only after I long press (activate slot 2, which could possibly be
associated to the CCID mode)?
The other way round: Is it possible to associate CCID to a slot (1 or 2)
?? or is it never associated to any slot. But CCID is rather
activated/deactivated by setting the CCID mode.

If CCID mode is enabled (the modes are not mutually exclusive, they are usually all enabled), this tool will prefer it as a transport mode. That is probably why you are failing to connect to the key. It is not related to the two slots (short press or long press) in any way, it functions as a smart card reader with a smart card inserted in it.  The `--touch-eject` flag can only be used when the device is in CCID mode _only_, and I wouldn't recommend it because it would prevent you from using the U2F and OTP features of the YubiKey.

> OTP:
Is that correct ? : The OTP mode must be configured to slot 1 and/or 2.
If done so, it can then be activated after insertion of the yk by either
a short or a long press on the yk button. Which will ask the device to
trigger a OTP.
At the same time a Yubikey-OTP programmed slot allows also always to
do a Yubikey Challenge-Response using the AES secret key ?
Is it possible to configure a slot to ONLY Yubikey OTP or ONLY Yubikey
Challenge-Response?
And what about the HMAC Challenge-Response? Is there also a link to OTP
(maybe the OATH-HOTP ?) Or can it only exist as a separate slot
configuration ?

So the term OTP here can refer to (at least) two things. If the transport mode OTP is enabled, the two YubiKey Slots, long press and short press, can be configured and used. These slots can have one of the following credentials configured: a [Yubico OTP](https://developers.yubico.com/OTP/) (which is what comes preconfigured in the short press slot on a new key), a static password, a challenge-response credential, a OATH-HOTP credential. All this functionality is found in the `$ ykman slot` commands.

I hope I clarified some stuff. Thanks for your questions, they expose in what areas documentation is lacking, even though as you mention I think support is a better channel for these more general questions.

",{},MEMBER,User,False
