8782,IssueCommentEvent,2015-09-08 14:49:00+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,779391,zsimpson,779641,Parsely,104782850,138589963,"It's the very first thing I do. Essentially I just get the consumer then I call reset_offsets if there's anything in the topic. That if statement was necessary do deal with topics that didn't have any messages on them yet.

```
	topic = kafka_client.topics[self.topic_id]
	consumer_group_id = 'kayak-'+str(uuid.uuid1())
	consumer = topic.get_simple_consumer( consumer_group_id )

	offsets = list(set([ res.offset[0] for p, res in topic.latest_available_offsets().items() ]))
	if not (len(offsets) == 1 and offsets[0] == -1):
		consumer.reset_offsets( [ (v, -1) for k,v in topic.partitions.items() ] )
```

I replaced this code with

```
	topic = kafka_client.topics[self.topic_id]
	consumer_group_id = 'kayak-'+str(uuid.uuid1())
	consumer = topic.get_simple_consumer( consumer_group_id )

	offsets = list(set([ res.offset[0] for p, res in topic.latest_available_offsets().items() ]))
	if not (len(offsets) == 1 and offsets[0] == -1):
		for k,v in topic.partitions.items():
			consumer.reset_offsets( [ (v, -1) ] )

```

And that seems to bypass the issue. Maybe because it slowed it down? Not really sure.
",{},,User,False
