8795,IssueCommentEvent,2015-06-19 23:59:17+00:00,4978045,Parsely/pykafka,694341,zhynxn,779641,Parsely,89213362,113679416,"Thanks Emmett for quick answer. I modify my code based on that.

For my 3rd question, i am thinking instead of stop the program, I want to
disconnect gracefully the kafka client connection. However, I do not find
it in document.



On Fri, Jun 19, 2015 at 3:27 PM, Emmett J. Butler <notifications@github.com>
wrote:

> Hi,
>
>    1. If the producer encounters an error, it will log it as a warning
>    <https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/master/pykafka/producer.py#L157-L175>
>    or in some cases raise an exception
>    <https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/master/pykafka/producer.py#L194>.
>    The producer handles retrying failed messages, so you can simply produce
>    inside of a try...except like this:
>
> try:
>     producer.produce(messages)
> except ProduceFailureError:
>     deal_with_error()
>
>
>    1.
>
>    When you call consumer.stop(), the consumer's fetch worker thread is
>    halted
>    <https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/blob/master/pykafka/simpleconsumer.py#L272-L273>.
>    This means that it will stop making requests to the kafka server for more
>    messages. However, it is possible (and likely) that after a call to
>    stop(), the consumer's internal queues will still contain messages
>    that were fetched before stop() was called. Thus, you will still be
>    able to call consumer.consume() until the queues are empty. If you
>    want to be certain that you've consumed all of the messages that have been
>    fetched, you can set the consumer_timeout_ms kwarg to some small
>    number greater than zero and call consume(block=True)
>    until it returns None.
>    2.
>
>    I'm not certain what you mean in this question. The BalancedConsumer
>    is the only type of pykafka consumer that registers itself in ZooKeeper. If
>    you want to consume a topic with multiple processes, you can use several
>    BalancedConsumers (one in each process) all sharing the same
>    consumer_group argument. See the documentation on BalancedConsumer here
>    <http://pykafka.readthedocs.org/en/latest/api/balancedconsumer.html>.
>
> —
> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub
> <https://github.com/Parsely/pykafka/issues/184#issuecomment-113661386>.
>
",{},,User,False
