8945,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-21 22:03:56+00:00,2014929,scikit-image/scikit-image,6528957,grlee77,897180,scikit-image,273447377,346176122,"@blochl 
I assume that the precision issue you encountered only occurs for the ""fast"" version of the algorithm?  I see that you have changed both variants to use double precision, but I think only the fast, integral image approach will have a precision that decreases with increasing image size.  Can the same precision fix be achieved using double precision only for the `integral` array used in `_integral_image_2d` and `_integral_image_3d`?  This would allow keeping other variables in float32 to preserve memory.

I think changing the precision in the Cython code will cause non-local means denoising to now always return a  `np.float64` result instead of a `np.float32` one?

Separate from this PR, it might be nice if these transforms had an option to preserve floating point precision of the input.  In current master, running denoising on a `np.float64` input gives a `np.float32` denoised output.  This can be annoying when using metrics such as `compare_psnr` or `compare_ssim` to compare the denoised and original because these functions currently raise errors if the dtypes of the inputs don't match.

",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
