10037,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-26 21:56:01+00:00,3470471,FortAwesome/Font-Awesome,12229855,cherrador,1505683,FortAwesome,135911478,189498735,"@slauyama you are right, I have not tried those combinations before, but one day I will and I will be in trouble. So far I have used only to create bullets. Somehow in my mind, they will cascade each other. But not, because the CSS property is ```transform``` and it will be simple overridden. If there where a ```transform-scale``` and ```transform-rotate``` CSS properties, it will be a different story.

On the ```fa-lg``` the trick of the ```line-height``` is required to allow the ```vertical-align``` to give the effect that the icon grows from the center of the inherit ```line-height```, if not it will grow from the baseline (what ```fa-2x``` will do). Going smaller, so far using ```vertical-align``` is good enough to keep the icon center to the inherit ```line-height```

@tagliala Damn... this HTML5 still a moving target... As I previously said, this scale technique was applied last year when I was working with Firefox 38. Somewhere in the middle this limitation has been lifted. At the moment I don't have the current Firefox 44 installed to test (somebody could verify this), but I have 46 (Developer version) and I can confirm that I can go all the way down to 1px on the body without problem (of course everything looks like thumbnails) the rest of the ```em``` and ```%``` styles will scale accordingly.

If Firefox 44 already fixed the problem, so go ahead, and use font-size to reduce the size but keep the vertical-align for the reason I explain it before. Also, even that the correct scale should be 2/3, I will recommend to use rounded numbers instead of infinite decimal. Again by experience, last month, I had found that Chrome has a bug rounding decimals when it's calculating the final line-height. This matters at smaller sizes because things could not align properly. I could point to a demo of this, but I do not want to deviate the point of this thread. Again, maybe in a few releases they could fix this bug.",{},,User,False
