10713,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-09 00:02:30+00:00,30509483,clab/dynet,154475,redpony,2374376,clab,212233168,285210664,"On Wed, Mar 8, 2017 at 7:23 PM, Joel Grus <notifications@github.com> wrote:

> OK, I made a first attempt at a more scala-like interface. It's not
> complete (and not documented), but you can see it here:
>
> https://github.com/allenai/dynet/tree/scaly/swig/src/
> main/scala/edu/cmu/dynet
>
> At a high level, the changes are
>
>    - moved the SWIG bindings into edu.cmu.dynet.internal (but otherwise
>    left them untouched)
>    - created a bunch of Scala wrapper classes, each of which wraps a
>    package-private instance of the ""internal"" (SWIG-generated) Java class, and
>    has methods that delegate to that instance. Basically, no one who uses this
>    API should ever see/know about any of the SWIG-generated Java classes
>    - gave everything scala-like names
>    - simplified the _Vector wrappers and made them implement IndexedSeq
>    so that they mostly ""feel like"" natural scala collections
>    - replaced the dim() helper function with factory methods in the Dim
>    object
>    - put the singleton ComputationGraph in the ComputationGraph object,
>    and moved all its methods to methods on that object
>    - accordingly, removed ComputationGraph from all function signatures
>    - versioned Expressions (as in the python code)
>    - instead of wrapping all the ParameterInit subclasses, I just made
>    their ""constructors"" factory methods on the ParameterInit companion
>    object
>    - all of the bare Expression-generating functions are now members of
>    the Expression companion object
>
> I updated all the examples and most of the tests. Probably just by looking
> at the examples you can get a good flavor of how it would work.
>
> --
>
> This version should be much more idiomatic Scala (at the expense of having
> two levels of wrapper code), but I don't know that it ""emphasizes the
> functional programming aspects"", can you say more about what you mean by
> that?
>
Here is one example of what I meant. You can think of RNNBuilders as
executing a recursive function on a sequence of input Expressions. Yes, we
wrote a C++ function that does this for some standard types of recurrent
networks, but if I had been writing DyNet from scratch in Scala (or Haskell
or whatever), the builder interface would have looked entirely different
than the one we have in C++ since Scala does this sort of thing in much
more beautiful ways than C++ ever could.

Here's the recursive definition of an RNN: the base case returns h_0 (a
learned expression, or 0); then recursively you apply tanh(W*[h_{t-1}; x_t]
+ b). Are you encoding a sequence and just want the final encoding? Well,
then just execute this as a foldLeft which creates the intermediate values
but doesn't return them to the user; only h_t is returned. Are you going to
attend to them later (e.g., in an attention based model)? Then use
scanLeft. Both of these take the same function which is the definition of
the RNN cell. It's a simple matter to change the definition of the RNN cell
from a simple RNN to a GRU. The code is factored beautifully, and there is
no new API with funny names to learn, just standard Scala functions like
fold and scan. What are the inputs to the RNN? Well, anything that
generates a list.

Why didn't I push for this in Python which could have also had a more
Pythonic interface? Well, Python can be a little slow and so we wanted a
fast interface, but Scala is quite fast, so I would be more than happy to
see the C++-accented builder interfaces disappear from Scala in favor of
native implementations. Of course, I realize that rewriting definitions of
RNNs and LSTMs is more work for you, and we've got nice and tested
definitions in the C++ code, so having both around, but I think a
functional language with idiomatic definitions of RNNs (and Recursive NNs,
etc etc) would be really cool. Most of the computational work, at the end
of the day, will be done by the C++ backend when it gets down to number
crunching, but you will have new and exciting ways to create differentiable
computations.

Does this make sense?

> Anyway, please let me know what you think of this approach, or if you see
> any changes that would make it nicer to use.
>
> —
