10723,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-17 15:48:26+00:00,6248645,ARM-DOE/pyart,1050278,jjhelmus,2540600,ARM-DOE,68997820,94013265,"@kirknorth How large of time period were the dealiasing routines run on in a single pass?  Both algorithms make the assumption that the velocities in the sweeps or chunks of data they operate on should be smoothly varying.  In the data linked it looks like a large shear event at approximate 2030 UTC is forcing all velocities prior to that time to have an extra nyquist added.  If this was excluded from the analysis my guess it that the corrections would be improved.  Not exactly a solution but an explanation...

Next week I'm hoping to have some time to add some debugging and logging code to the region dealiasing algorithm so I can get a better handle on what is going on during cases like this.  I have some ideas but I'd like to verify them before speculating on the cause and suggesting solutions.  

One simple idea to try  is to rerun the algorithm with a higher value for the **interval_splits** parameter.  Setting that parameter to 4 or 5 will further segment the initial velocity.  The algorithm will take longer to complete but may give improved results.",{},,User,False
