10959,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-29 14:18:37+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,242750,tseaver,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,180051974,250479449,"@pdknsk Thanks for the report!  You are correct that we currently have no support for addressing a specific generation of a blob.

ISTM that the `generation` flag should probably be passed to `Blob.__init__` (and through `Bucket.blob()`, because it should affect other operations as well. 

API endpoints taking the `generation` query string parameter, which should be mapped from the blob's `generation` property, if set:

- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/get
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/delete
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/getIamPolicy
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/insert (?!)
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/patch (?!)
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/setIamPolicy (?!)
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/testIamPermissions
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/update (?!)

The `(?!)` is because it confounds my expectations to be updating a historical generation of the resource:  I thought I understood that updating the current version was how a new generation gets created.

API endpoints taking the `source_generation` query string parameter, which would be mapped from the source blob's `generation` property, if set:

- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/copy
- https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/objects/rewrite

We should probably also plan to support the various ""conditional"" parameters that these APIs support (`ifGenerationMatch`, `ifGenerationNotMatch`, `ifMetagenerationMatch`, `ifMetagenerationNotMatch`).
",{},,User,False
10965,IssueCommentEvent,2018-05-15 19:13:20+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,13599208,anmol1vw13,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,320972454,389280982,"I find `subscriber` in **0.32.0** more stable than `subscriber_experimental` in **0.34.0**. That stops too, but it happens after a day or two not unlike `subscriber_experimental` which goes offline every two hours.",{},NONE,User,False
