11002,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-24 20:45:41+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python,7953259,mikelambert,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,216310253,289138575,"I'm relatively new to Dataflow, but AFAIK pickling is *the* serialization method used by Dataflow. They run multiple worker instances, all on the same GCE image, with the same python and package code versions, so I'm guaranteed identical code running on both ends of the pickling. In Dataflow, I yield/return python objects from one function in the pipeline, and they are magically sent as an argument to another function (possibly running on a different worker instance).

It's possible I could manually serialize everything myself, into protobufs or strings or another such serialization format. But those strings would then still be pickled anyway...so... :)

(I debugged and fixed YT pickling bwcompat issues when migrating from python2.2->2.4 at Google, so yes I'm aware of many reasons to consider pickling an anti-pattern :P, but I'm not sure how many apply of those reasons apply here...)

CC-ing Google Dataflow engineers (@aaltay and @robertwb) who worked on pickling, that can probably speak to the decisions and justifications better than myself as an ex-Google just-a-Dataflow-newbie.
",{},,User,False
