11179,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-25 21:37:21+00:00,4086616,shadowsocks/shadowsocks,7109762,lepasserby,3006190,shadowsocks,39876845,96282543,"Okay, if I may humbly enter this discussion (I am manageriat :) not real coder, but hey, I do think I have a neat idea here), if our only concern is statistical indistingushability, I think your proposal can be simplified to use a single password.

So, let's see:
your proposal:
 
IV1 + ver + userhash + IV2 + addr + data
 

Assumption 1:
IV1 and IV2 are strongly pseudorandom nonces (I don't know if your IVs are properly pseudorandom nonces, but they should be, for indistinguishibility's sake) you can use hash of IV1 as ""key"" to encrypt ver and userhash

Assumption 2:
addr is actually encrypted with user's password, just like data 
(it was not obvious from your description, you said <i>""ver + userhash is encrypted using key, data is encrypted using user's password.""</i> but it seems prudent and reasonable to encrypt the address too, so I assume address is encrypted using user's password)

So it will be 
IV1 + ENC<sup>Key</sup>(ver+userhash) + IV2 + addr + data

ENC= whatever cipher in whatever mode of operation you deem necessary.
I suggest ENC = RC4-MD5 because it's fast and we aren't aiming for security. and it's a stream cipher so we don't need to even bother with modes

Key = hash of IV1 (you can use md5 or SHA or whatever)

So... 
Now, everything on the wire looks random and passive deep packet inspection would see neither ""ver"" nor ""addr"" nor even ""userhash"", and IV1, IV2 are already pseudorandom nonces.
 
",{},,User,False
