11534,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-25 08:46:01+00:00,53788968,behave/behave-django,665072,bittner,3344102,behave,216930256,289198590,"This is probably not related to behave-django as such. You'd have to provide more details, though, ideally steps to reproduce the error.

You may find more helpful hints in similar issues on the web, e.g.

- [Django Test — Unable to drop and recreate test database](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/38999203/django-test-unable-to-drop-and-recreate-test-database) (StackOverflow)
- https://code.djangoproject.com/ticket/22420
- https://github.com/Fantomas42/django-blog-zinnia/issues/476
- [Concurrent Jenkins builds of a Django application](http://blog.richard.do/index.php/2014/09/concurrent-jenkins-builds-of-a-django-application/) (a blog)
- https://github.com/grosser/parallel_tests/issues/412

The last issue suggests that the problem is related to Postgres alone, not even Django. At least the error message comes directly from there. Some other application may use your database while you run the tests.

Please let us know when find the culprit, so others can profit too.",{},,User,False
11538,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-21 13:55:00+00:00,30618733,prometheus/client_python,7115638,brian-brazil,3380462,prometheus,307253054,374944613,"I avoid dependencies in this module, so I'd prefer not to add one if it isn't strictly needed.",{},OWNER,User,False
11540,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-29 12:47:55+00:00,30618733,prometheus/client_python,270571,WoLpH,3380462,prometheus,244124739,401343953,"**DISCLAIMER: THIS CODE IS NOT RECOMMENDED IN PRODUCTION**

I've quickly hacked together this bit and to my untrained eye it appears to function correctly:
```python
class ProcessCollector(prometheus_client.ProcessCollector):

    def __init__(self, namespace='', pid=lambda: 'self', proc='/proc'
                 registry=prometheus_client.REGISTRY, labels=None):
        self.labels = labels
        prometheus_client.ProcessCollector.__init__(
            self, namespace, pid, proc, registry)

    def collect(self):
        results = prometheus_client.ProcessCollector.collect(self)
        for result in results:
            result._labelnames = tuple(self.labels)
            result.samples = [(name, self.labels, value)
                              for (name, _, value) in result.samples]

        return results

    def describe(self):
        return []
```

It's less than ideal though, especiallly having to overwrite the `describe` because the collector doesn't take labels into account.",{},NONE,User,False
