12013,IssueCommentEvent,2016-02-27 21:23:07+00:00,12407457,Exa-Networks/exabgp,8971544,nskalis,5339170,Exa-Networks,123306804,189728891,"hi @fdebonneval @thomas-mangin 

elasticsearch is going to explode if you store the next_hop value as a key and prefixes as values, so you can do sth like 
```
'next_hop' 			: message['neighbor']['message']['update']['announce']['ipv4 unicast'].keys()[0],
'net_block' 			: message['neighbor']['message']['update']['announce']['ipv4 unicast'].values()[0].keys()
```
and in order to store that, the best way in order to be able to query subnets is described here:
```
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29770043/how-can-i-store-and-search-multiple-ipv4-and-ipv6-subnets-in-elasticsearch
```
i hope i helped somehow",{},,User,False
12014,IssueCommentEvent,2016-10-04 17:07:45+00:00,12407457,Exa-Networks/exabgp,1227755,thomas-mangin,5339170,Exa-Networks,180901276,251450193,"@spakka having written the code and understanding it well, I really believe it may be a bug/side effect of the python garbage collector.

After a review, we should never need to do this on close, as we always explicitely called close before removing all references to the object.

So I will simply remove the code later on and close this issue, the `__del__` function can just go.

We found some weird issue like this in the past (where the caching of object was broken but the dev would not fix the issue as it would affect deployed application which - while really annoying when the code does not work as should - is good as it does not break real world deployments).

https://mail.python.org/pipermail/new-bugs-announce/2008-July/002344.html
for the details 😜 ",{},,User,False
12019,IssueCommentEvent,2016-04-14 01:42:01+00:00,12407457,Exa-Networks/exabgp,14178956,liuheyang,5339170,Exa-Networks,145107861,209717090,"@thomas-margin, hi, we connect Exabgp to huawei switch. the problem have been solved, thanks your help. and i will close the issue!",{},,User,False
