12372,IssueCommentEvent,2015-07-26 18:02:09+00:00,4744355,soft-matter/trackpy,2985325,nkeim,5857177,soft-matter,80525783,125023437,"OK, this is fascinating: When you attempt to merge this into master (hopefully after merging fixes by @caspervdw and myself), you'll find that [`test_uncertainty_failure`](https://github.com/soft-matter/trackpy/pull/252) fails, and you won't know why. Turns out that the bandpass done in `uncertainty.roi()` changes just enough that it no longer leads to `ep == NaN` (instead, we get `ep == -0.0`!). I couldn't find a new set of parameters in `test_uncertainty_failure` to fix this. 

What does fix this test is to not have `uncertainty.roi()` do its own bandpass. (The test calls `locate()` with `preprocess=False`, because the test image is already built from gaussians.) 

So, 2 questions for discussion:

1. Why does this fix the problem? I.e. why the new `bandpass` behavior so different in this instance?

2. Why is `uncertainty.roi()` even doing a bandpass when `preprocess=False`? If the user calls `locate()` with `preprocess=False`, shouldn't trackpy presume that the image is already bandpassed? In the [discussion on uncertainty estimation](https://github.com/soft-matter/trackpy/pull/239), there was some mention of ways to accommodate users who do their own bandpass, but I can't see how the current code does. The present behavior instead acts as a performance ""gotcha."" Shouldn't `locate()` accept *both* `image` and `raw_image` when `preprocess=False`?",{},,User,False
12374,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-17 23:21:54+00:00,4744355,soft-matter/trackpy,2985325,nkeim,5857177,soft-matter,81954369,131990517,"I figured it was something like that. This is a big, big deal, because it means that *most* code that calls trackpy needs to be edited to give comparable results. It would be as though we switched from diameter to radius — except the conversion is not necessarily straightforward.

How can we explain this in the release notes? We need to explain the reason for this change and show an easy way to convert `minmass`. How about

> trackpy has a new method of calculating feature ""mass"" that compensates for bit depth and the details of preprocessing. This means that masses are more likely to be consistent under changes in image brightness or format. To obtain results comparable to those from older trackpy versions, you may have to adjust your `minmass` parameter (and other parts of your code that use the mass). A good rule of thumb is…

…is there one?

Also, this really tips the scales for making the release notes required reading for anyone doing an upgrade.",{},,User,False
