12442,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-02 00:03:11+00:00,35912257,AuthorizeNet/sdk-python,2636532,pwag42,6014037,AuthorizeNet,321785582,394038927,"You may want to consider using a different word, then. What you just described varies enough from the dictionary and vernacular definitions of ""engineering"" that I suspect you'll probably spend a lot of time misunderstood and/or explaining yourself.

Also, that every commit must produce a production-ready build is, while a nice sentiment, hardly a settled best-practice. Git is a version control system, not a package manager. Pull requests exist _because_ breaking code changes into easily-reviewed chunks (that don't necessarily work on their own) is expected and acceptable behavior. PyPI (and other package indexes) exist because the source isn't even expected to be production-ready 100% of the time.

And this is more of a tone thing, but phrases like ""you are being negligent"" are unnecessarily accusatory for open-source software.",{},NONE,User,False
