12548,IssueCommentEvent,2015-04-16 21:56:50+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,1821014,krancour,6117407,deis,53052185,93848801,"Also, just for the sake of minimizing any overlapping efforts in this thread, I am currently hacking on `deisctl` to create an ""install wizard.""  It's rough around the edges still, but I am continuing to iterate on it.

I'll socialize my basic approach now in case anyone wants to comment and steer me off an undesirable path.

1. I've added utility functions for interactively prompting the operator for yes/no responses and other information.

2. I've added functions to config.go that allow programmatically setting and getting etcd config values _without_ necessarily feeding in an array of command line args parsed by docopt.  i.e., Can be used to programmatically interact with etcd with minimal hassle.

3. I've been working to modify the implementation of the `install` command.  Currently it _only_ kicks off the wizard, but I will also put back the functionality that allows it to install an individual component.  The wizard delegates the collection of different thematically-related bits of information to helper methods that use *#*1 to interactively get the operator to opt into / out of various components (storage subsystem and database) _and_ collects any information needed to compensate for the absence of any component they opt out of.  For instance, if opting out of the database, database connection details are collected.  All the information that is collected is stored in etcd using *#*2.  _Also_ information is stored in etcd about _which_ components are installed.  (This is important.)

4. I've been working to modify the implementation of the `start` command.  Currently it _only_ can be used to start the platform (or more precisely, the subset of the platform that the operator opted into in *#*3).  I will add back in the ability to start individual components.

5. I also intend to update the implementation of `stop` and `uninstall` commands to limit themselves in scop (similar to *#*4) to stopping / unloading _just_ those components that the operator opted into in *#*3.

I _just_ learned go (though I have ample experience with other languages).  I learned it specifically so I could hack on this issue.  It's possible that my code is not 100% idiomatic just yet, as I am still grokking all the golang idioms.  The interactive portions of the code have some very minor smells to them that I am trying to address.  Short of putting some sort of rules engine in place (which seems like way overkill, IMO), I guess I was sort of expecting the interactive (wizard) portion to have some minor smells.

I guess what I am trying to say: I'm socializing the approach because I want feedback.  By all means, stop be if this is an abomination... just be gentle.

My WIP can be seen in this branch: https://github.com/krancour/deis/tree/install-wizard-wip

If someone else (@Blystad ?) wants to run point on modification to images and unit files, I think we could have a comprehensive solution that potentially puts closure on this thread pretty quickly.",{},,User,False
