12824,IssueCommentEvent,2017-01-04 00:00:34+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,881019,dhirschfeld,6392739,conda,192888989,270260385,"I think I'm having a similar issue. I have `channel_priority` set to `false` because when I update I want the latest version of a package irrespective of whichever channel in my channel list it comes from i.e. I should never see the message:
> The following packages will be SUPERCEDED by a higher-priority channel:

It might be possible to see that message if it was swapping the package for the exact same version (i.e. not downgrading) from the ""higher priority"" channel, but that would be somewhat redundant and contrary to my expectation that channel priority means treat all channels the same.

In my case whenever I do an `update --all` it wants to *downgrade* freetype:
```
The following packages will be UPDATED:

    beautifulsoup4: 4.5.1-py35_0              --> 4.5.3-py35_0
    conda-build:    2.0.12-py35_0             --> 2.1.0-py35_0
    pyflakes:       1.3.0-py35_0              --> 1.4.0-py35_0
    pymc3:          3.0rc4-py35_0 conda-forge --> 3.0rc6-py35_0 conda-forge

The following packages will be SUPERCEDED by a higher-priority channel:

    freetype:       2.7-vc14_0    conda-forge [vc14] --> 2.5.5-vc14_1              [vc14]
```
...however upgrading freetype after the fact works fine:
```
λ conda update --force freetype
Fetching package metadata .........................
Solving package specifications: ..........

Package plan for installation in environment C:\Python:

The following packages will be UPDATED:

    freetype: 2.5.5-vc14_1 [vc14] --> 2.7-vc14_0 conda-forge [vc14]

Proceed ([y]/n)? y

Pruning extracted packages from the cache ...
[      COMPLETE      ]|##################################################| 100%
Extracting packages ...
[      COMPLETE      ]|##################################################| 100%
Unlinking packages ...
[      COMPLETE      ]|##################################################| 100%
Linking packages ...
[      COMPLETE      ]|##################################################| 100%
```

Note: I *think* this may be due to a mis-specified dependency somewhere in which case the behaviour is correct but the message is misleading - i.e. the message should specify that it is being downgraded due to version conflicts rather than channel priority (which should never happen)
",{},,User,False
