13082,IssueCommentEvent,2017-06-02 16:15:14+00:00,51040886,Azure/azure-cli,5723682,tjprescott,6844498,Azure,232885110,305835544,"Hi @alexeyshishkin01, in the case of 1, this is by design across Azure. One of the main reasons for this is because if you ran a script to set up your infrastructure, and that script failed for some reason (intermittent service issue or something), you want to be able to re-run that script and not have it fail because your VM already exists, nor would you want it to create another VM (which it couldn't anyways because the ID would be the same). 

As far as issuing a warning, there is no way for us to do this without making additional REST calls against the user's quota to see if the VM already exists. As a CLI design principle, we purposely avoid this. However, I've opened an issue for this specifically (#3593) so we can gather more feedback on this. Like anything, if enough people want it... :smile:

That the NSG is left over after a failed template deployment is actually by-design. However, expecting transactional behavior is not unreasonable (and not impossible) so I've created issue #3595 to gather additional feedback and track this potential feature work.

Regarding the FQDN--I ran it twice with different values for --public-ip-address-dns-name and it did in fact update the FQDN. However, your issue did alert me that some of the template based creates make not be fully goal-seeking.  I created a separate issue to track that  (#3592).

I'm going to close this issue since the potentially actionable feature work items have been moved to new issues, but feel free to continue the discussion here (or in the other threads) as you feel appropriate. :grin:",{},,User,False
