14180,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-01 16:28:31+00:00,24245737,projectmesa/mesa,596978,dmasad,8754505,projectmesa,284056200,354662171,"Hi Kevin,
I think that if you have both Python 2 and 3 installed, and you want to use the global package folders (as opposed to virtual environments), you need to install packages with `pip3` (see e.g. [here](https://askubuntu.com/questions/412178/how-to-install-pip-for-python-3-in-ubuntu-12-04-lts)). 

Another alternative is to create a Python 3 [virtual environment ](https://realpython.com/blog/python/python-virtual-environments-a-primer/), and install Mesa inside of it. That's what I'd recommend -- especially since Mesa does update often enough that you want to make it easy for you to either keep a static version associated with a specific project, and to reinstall it if you want access to newer features. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
