14333,IssueCommentEvent,2015-05-05 12:17:46+00:00,1151051,django-oscar/django-oscar,509427,maikhoepfel,9057806,django-oscar,73044085,99064005,"@mvantellingen: Thanks for doing the stores PR. Much appreciated!
Migration should be compatible, yes. The issue is a different one. Django 1.8 [shipped with a few migrations](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.8/releases/1.8/#default-emailfield-max-length-increased-to-254). For example, the default length of an `EmailField` increased, and `User.last_login` can now be `None`. Because we have models using an `EmailField`, `makemigrations` will pick up those changes when switching to Django 1.8. But if we bundle those created migrations with Oscar, they will be fed to all Oscar users, including Django 1.7.

The scenarios I can imagine are:
-  Bundle migrations of highest supported Django version. Then we might run into a situation where a lower Django version doesn't have the matching code changes (e.g. be unable to deal with `User.last_login` being `None).
- Bundle migrations of lowest supported Django version. When running with a higher Django version, the user will see model changes that aren't reflected in migrations. I think if then running `makemigrations`, they would be created inside the virtualenv, which wouldn't persist across deployments, leading to a messy situation for the user.
- Bundle migrations of highest supported Django version, wrap in a `if django.VERSION < (1,8)`. I'm not entirely sure of the consequences, but it's worth investigating.
- Ship no migrations. Are they even necessary? Can't we generally ask the user to run `makemigrations`, even for non-customised apps?
- Any other approach.",{},,User,False
