14337,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-23 11:08:31+00:00,8760389,django-oscar/django-oscar-api,52858,specialunderwear,9057806,django-oscar,213426758,288686332,"Hi oscarapi offers you a way to integrate payments, but does not offer any payment fuctionality by itself, because it is to specific to the payment providers.

What oscarapi want you to do is as follows:

implement a view and register it's url:
```
urls = urlpatterns('',
   url(r""^paymentsetup/(?P<pk>[0-9]+)/$"", TheViewThatSetsUpPayment.as_view(), name='api-payment'),
  # the rest of your views
)
```

If you do this, every order object that is created with the checkout api, get's a payment url,that you can use to move onto payment. So that means payment comes AFTER checkout. Same way as in a physical shop, the cassiere will scan all the items you want to buy, and then tells you what you need to pay. Now you can pay with credit card or PIN or cash. This is no different.

What you should implement in that view (TheViewThatSetsUpPayment) is setting up the payment with the payment provider. The view get's the order is as a parameter, so you can query for it and read any details you need for the payment provider. The you should make some requests to the payment provider to set up the payment. Usually they will then provide you with a url that you should redirect your client to. So that is also what you should do in your ``TheViewThatSetsUpPayment`` after setting up the payment with the payment provider, at the end of the view return a redirect to the payment provider's url.

If you don't redirect to an external site, but have all the payment pages in your own site, just redirect to an internal page.

That is all the support we offer, all the stuff you need to do to confirm payment, create payment events with payment sources, change the order status, should be in your own code, because we feel it is very specific to whichever provider you are using.

So the library you linked above does implement features that handle Payment events and order status for you. @crgwbr maybe you can fill in some blanks on how this is supposed to fit in the story I just told.",{},,User,False
