14553,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-17 10:58:33+00:00,26661222,tinode/chat,5938143,or-else,9325720,tinode,341750926,405543088,"usrPfh1tgGXwL8 and usrlJoTtWc5MJA represent 64 bit values. Take a 64 bit value, apply base64. Base64 converts every 6 bits into a single character: 64/6 = 10 full 6-bit sequences + 4 bits of overflow for a total of 11 characters.

To generate the name of the p2p topic the two UIDs are concatenated, the smaller value goes first. In this case usrlJoTtWc5MJA is smaller than usrPfh1tgGXwL8. The values are converted into 8 bytes each, then concatenated to create 16 bytes or 128 bits. Then the 16 bytes are converted to string using base64. Like before the first 10 characters are the same, then the 4 bits of overflow are combined with the first 2 bits of the first byte of the second UID. In this case it accidentally produced the same character `A`. Then the subsequent bits are aligned differently than before and produce different characters. ",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
14554,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-02 04:43:55+00:00,26661222,tinode/chat,5938143,or-else,9325720,tinode,337357071,401671086,"1. Taylor Christie has answered this.

> When I refresh regularly

That's a highly inefficient and it's not how it's supposed to be used. Tinode is not a passive database. It will notify you automatically of all events.

2. 
