14626,IssueCommentEvent,2015-03-29 19:20:34+00:00,26876372,dateutil/dateutil,1377457,pganssle,9849410,dateutil,58576986,87459396,"@ryanss Good catch, but I think that the support actually should be made more explicit. Right now, it's basically a coincidence that this works, because `relativedelta` doesn't explicitly check if it's been given a float or an integer, and all relative information at the level of a day or smaller are first cast to `timedelta` during addition operations. When a `timedelta` object is passed a fractional argument, it converts the remaining fraction to seconds (which is added to the existing seconds argument). So:

    >>> timedelta(days=1.48, seconds=4)
    datetime.timedelta(1, 41476)

This doesn't work if you use anything bigger than a week, though (weeks are implictly converted to days), since those are manually converted and expecting an `int`:

    >>> rd = relativedelta.relativedelta(months=1.5)
    >>> datetime(2014, 1, 1) + rd
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    TypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)
    <ipython-input-6-245d768deca6> in <module>()
    ----> 1 datetime(2014, 1, 1) + rd

    dateutil\relativedelta.pyc in __radd__(self, other)
         317     def __radd__(self, other):
    --> 318         return self.__add__(other)
        320     def __rsub__(self, other):

    dateutil\relativedelta.pyc in __add__(self, other)
        288                 year -= 1
        289                 month += 12
    --> 290         day = min(calendar.monthrange(year, month)[1],
        291                   self.day or other.day)
        292         repl = {""year"": year, ""month"": month, ""day"": day}

    C:\Python27\lib\calendar.pyc in monthrange(year, month)
        119     if not 1 <= month <= 12:
        120         raise IllegalMonthError(month)
    --> 121     day1 = weekday(year, month, 1)
        122     ndays = mdays[month] + (month == February and isleap(year))
        123     return day1, ndays

    C:\Python27\lib\calendar.pyc in weekday(year, month, day)
        111     """"""Return weekday (0-6 ~ Mon-Sun) for year (1970-...), month (1-12),
        112        day (1-31).""""""
    --> 113     return datetime.date(year, month, day).weekday()

    TypeError: integer argument expected, got float

I think that if we want to support this sort of thing, then it needs to work for all relative arguments, and at the very least `relativedelta.__repr__` needs to be updated to reflect the fact that this is happening:

    >>> rd = relativedelta.relativedelta(days=1.48, seconds=4)
    >>> rd
    relativedelta(days=+1, seconds=+4)

    >>> rd.days, rd.seconds
    (1.48, 4)

The other problem is that *absolute* information arguments (`year`, `month`, `day`), *also* accept floats, but can't actually handle them.

I think that my plan moving forward on this is to do 3 things for the 2.5.0 release:
1. Add a deprecation warning when constructing `relativedelta` objects using absolute floats, indicating that this will no longer be possible in future releases.
2. Add explicit support for relative floats of all sizes, applied only during the actual arithmetic operations (e.g. `relativedelta(days=1.5, hours=2)` will store `days` as 1.5 and `hours` as 2 rather than storing `days` as 1 and `hours` as 14). This will be reflected in the `__repr__` method.
3. Add a method which takes a `relativedelta` object with floating point relative arguments and returns an equivalent representation using only integer values for each argument. This will work like `timedelta`, with each relative argument adding to lower ones if necessary.",{},,User,False
14631,IssueCommentEvent,2016-03-24 02:58:19+00:00,26876372,dateutil/dateutil,14852019,tim-one,9849410,dateutil,142229936,200631221,"There's little you can do about arithmetic.  If I understand it, this approach won't be wholly compatible with pytz or with a PEP 495 implementation.

It's _intended_ that arithmetic within a single zone follow the ""naive time"" model:  that every day has exactly 24 hours.  With a few exceptions, datetime arithmetic in Python ignores the tzinfo members, except that datetime += timedelta mindlessly copies the source tzinfo to the result.  The arithmetic itself acts as if tzinfo were `None`.

The intent is that if people _want_ their datetimes to jump around to match local daylight (etc) transitions, then they should either use timestamps, or convert to UTC, do arithmetic in UTC, and convert back to local time at the end.

The unfortunate (we wouldn't do this if we could do it all over) exceptions are subtracting, or comparing, two datetimes.  Then *if* they have the same tzinfo member, the tzinfo member is again wholly ignored.  But if the tzinfo members differ (not the same object), both datetimes are effectively converted to UTC before the subtraction/comparison.

So, e.g., suppose we have two local datetimes `d1` and `d2` with `d1` corresponding to the later of an ambiguous local hour (so has `fold==1`) and `d2` the earlier (so has `fold==0`).  Under the PEP, they'll probably have the same tzinfo member, and then -- same as today! -- `d1 - d2` will be `0`:  tzinfo is ignored.  But under your scheme (if I understand it), they'll have distinct (not the same object) tzinfo members, and the subtraction will yield 1 hour.

The best way for users to get around this, when they care, is the intended way:  if they want ""timeline arithmetic"" (arithmetic that accounts for transitions moving the local clock around), they should work in UTC and convert back to the local zone when they're done.  The only thing that stops that working ""perfectly"" today is that it's currently not possible to do interzone conversions correctly in all cases (due to the current lack of an `isdst/fold` indicator to disambiguate ambiguous local times).  Alas, I still see no way to repair that, and preserve all the intents, short of storing `fold` in the datetime instance.
",{},,User,False
