14898,IssueCommentEvent,2015-10-08 16:58:43+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,1393014,mark-anders,10334301,marshmallow-code,110342219,146623295,"@sloria - Actually, I went with Polyfield and got it working.  I'm not sure why you decided to not support this scenario in Marshmallow core, but it's complicated enough that I think it would be a great thing to support out of the box, or at least have an official sample that's maintained with the current architecture.",{},,User,False
14899,IssueCommentEvent,2018-06-19 09:44:30+00:00,14284859,marshmallow-code/marshmallow,1767010,lafrech,10334301,marshmallow-code,333590129,398340485,"`required=False` (which should be implicit as it is the default) means that you may omit the key in input data, not that the value can be `None` or empty string.

To accept a `None` value, you'd need to add `allow_none=True`.

And of course, an empty string is valid for a `String` field but not for an `Email` field.

There's no way you can accept an empty string for an `Email` field. If you have no data, then the key/value pair should be omitted in input data.

Well, you could hack the `Email` field to accept an empty string, but this is probably not the right thing to do.",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
