15224,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-06 11:11:38+00:00,18302786,IDSIA/sacred,1160920,Qwlouse,11296960,IDSIA,278470102,363390725,"Hi. I'm sorry for not being able to fix this ATM. And while I'm happy to hear that you consider tackling this yourself, I think I should warn/discourage you: This is a tricky issue that probably requires changes in several places of the configuration system. My guess is that it would take me a full day to change this, so it would probably take you longer than that. The problem is that I am internally converting updates of the form `a.b=1` and `c={'d':2}` into an update dictionary like this `{'a': {'b': 1}, 'c': {'d': 2}}` before even handing it over to the config. So in order to use the former for setting `b` and the latter for setting the entirety of `c` this conversion needs to be removed. Then the `DogmaticDict` which is used to handle fixed values would have to be adjusted to treat these as different cases. Unfortunately, this class is not well documented and can be somewhat tricky to get right. 
Further, I have a half-done reimplementation of this part of the configuration system, which is meant to fix this issue, and also improve support for non-string keys. But this again would take some time to finish and integrate into sacred. 


So in summary, I cannot really recommend you working on this. But I think I might have a better workaround for you: 
``` python
@ex.config
def cfg():
    a = {}
    if not hasattr(a, 'fixed'):
        a = dict(b=1, c=2)
```
This is abusing the config mechanism and should lead to `a` being overwritten by all updates including  `python run.py print_config with a=""{'d':  3}""`. But not that in this case even `python run.py print_config with a.d=3""` will lead to a removal of `b` and `c`. It works because a will be a plain dictionary if there are no config updates for it, and otherwise it is going to be a `DogmaticDict`. 

",{},OWNER,User,False
