15653,IssueCommentEvent,2017-03-13 20:19:35+00:00,40328394,angr/angr,6720957,schieb,12520807,angr,212907949,286230782,"@frapik99 I suggest that you read up on lazy binding and the PLT/GOT. Then step through an example in a debugger.

In short, the indirect jump target will originally be the very next instruction in that stub which will first push an identifier and then pass control to the dynamic linker. The dynamic linker will pop the identifier, use it to locate the function you are trying to call (`malloc`), copy the address of that function to the GOT slot that is used in `0x7ffff7bab100  <malloc@plt+0>  jmp QWORD PTR [rip+0x22d1da]`, and jump into `malloc`.

Next time your code calls `malloc` via the PLT, its address has already been resolved and placed into the GOT, so control will flow (in)directly to `malloc`.",{},,User,False
