15713,IssueCommentEvent,2015-12-11 01:21:31+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,6732731,djnugent,12973369,dronekit,121425638,163802642,"I also confirmed gimbal read back is working. It does not give the actual IMU orientation of the gimbal but the last commanded orientation from the autopilot. This includes ROI, mavlink targeting, and, rc targeting. But it will not change if you poke your gimbal or rotate your copter.",{},,User,False
15714,IssueCommentEvent,2015-08-10 07:07:52+00:00,18188537,dronekit/dronekit-python,5368500,hamishwillee,12973369,dronekit,99989141,129332966,"@tcr3dr @mrpollo @djnugent  I have created an example ([see gist here](https://gist.github.com/hamishwillee/1ff5c3771eea307473c0#file-handle_message-py)) which shows how you might use ``set_mavlink_callback`` to the raw_imu message. The example is a little non-trivial in that it attaches the new object ``vehicle.raw_imu`` to the vehicle and hooks into the normal notifier mechanism so you can create callbacks and, after adding the handler, treat this as though it were an inbuilt attribute.

I would have liked to make this a separate module but there are two problems

* I don't think you can load a module/file that isn't properly in the path - ie you can't import a file ""in the same directory"" because the current directory is where MAVProxy starts, not where your first file is run from. Yes we could do some magic to add paths but not worth it here unless there ends up being an API to easily set current path from MAVProxy.
* ``set_mavlink_callback`` is a ""singleton"" - if I hook it in my module, then anyone adding a new observer in their script would break it.

I quite like this, because it is probably a more realistic way you might use the API and because we're not too fast to add new attributes. I dislike it because I would rather encourage people to add new APIs properly.

A question

1. Is this a reasonable example, or should I just do a basic one which simply accesses the values of the received message?",{},,User,False
