15860,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-27 13:45:11+00:00,43645564,ganga-devs/ganga,61316,milliams,13271048,ganga-devs,179228606,249869036,"Firstly, I'm not I see how this can cause data corruption? A job failing to load due to missing classes should create an `IncompleteObject`. This will never be flushed so there will be no damage to the data on disk.

Secondly, we've never done this sort of retroactive compatibility fix in the past. To first order, this is no different to when we added `LocalFile` or `GaudiExec`. Loading a job with those as attributes would fail in exactly the same way. We make no promise to our users that it is safe to run new jobs on a old version of Ganga. There are very few pieces of software that allow this sort of forward-compatibility.

There is some small special case here though in that a 6.2 job which is running, when loaded in 6.3 could automatically get these attributes added without the user's knowledge. Re-loading in 6.2 would then fail as you described. It would still be completely safe though to load it again in 6.3 as nothing should be lost in that cycle. The only reason we might want to make an exception in this one special case is that the credentials branch has a larger than usual chance of breaking users' workflow or introducing bugs and so to be kind to them we should perhaps make it possible to temporarily revert to 6.2.",{},,User,False
