16122,IssueCommentEvent,2017-09-27 19:14:19+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,17897861,ev-mp,14095512,IntelRealSense,260936078,332626292,"Hi @mtee, can you be more specific of what librealsense demo/app did not run correctly ?

As for the log messages you refer to are **warnings** that and are produced by another [videodev] kernel module, and they are not indicative of patch success or failure 
> [ 228.101516] **WARNING**: CPU: 0 PID: 3093 at /build/linux-hwe-0IbwuF/linux-hwe-4.8.0/drivers/media/v4l2-core/v4l2-ioctl.c:1286 v4l_enum_fmt+0xe24/0x1190 [videodev].

Actually, looking into the log you posted both the patching process and R200 enumeration of R200 completed successfully, 
In order check whether the required formats have been resolved you can run the following (requires 'v4l-utils' installed):

_v4l2-ctl --list-formats-ext -d /dev/video0
v4l2-ctl --list-formats-ext -d /dev/video1
v4l2-ctl --list-formats-ext -d /dev/video2_

and check whether there are unrecognized formats.

Moreover, in case you're using R200 only you may skip the patch completely since its format descriptions have already been upstreamed to Linux kernel since version 4.4.+.

",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
16124,IssueCommentEvent,2018-07-10 07:05:08+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,34384799,RealSense-Customer-Engineering,14095512,IntelRealSense,339389553,403722357,"[Realsense Customer Engineering Team Comment]
@pierref33
When run Python 2.x, you will need to have use pyrealsense build with python 2.x,  same for python 3.x
you can use the prebuilt library (built with python 2.7
32bit (x86) /64 bit (x64) type compatibility also matter

for detail you can refer to below link
https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/tree/development/wrappers/python

The precompiled binaries shipped with the installer assume **python2.7**. The error `ImportError: DLL load failed: The specified module could not be found` might indicate versions mismatch or architecture (x86 vs x64) mismatch.

1. Open `librealsense2.sln` that was created in the previous step, and build the `pyrealsense2` project
2. Open the output folder of the project (e.g `build\x64-Release\Release\`) and copy `pyrealsense2.pyd` into your python's `site-packages` (e.g `C:\Python27\Lib\site-packages`)
3. Alternatively, copy the build output (`realsense2.dll` and `pyrealsense2.pyd`) next to your script.

and please check if the microsoft 2015 (or 2017)  vc++ redistributable  (x64)  is also installed

you can use python example code to ensure your tools chain is correct

ex : C:\xxxx\librealsense\wrappers\python\examples\python-tutorial-1-depth.py",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
16126,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-09 17:31:47+00:00,46374199,IntelRealSense/librealsense,22654243,zivsha,14095512,IntelRealSense,295865669,364502385,"Hi @jangernert ,
Thanks for the PR! 
Your implementation look good, however, not all devices support advanced mode (e.g. SR300), and I'm not sure putting it as part of the Device class is the best design. In other places like this, we use the `as` and `is` keywords to cast the object to the requested interface. You can see this in `VideoFrame`, `Point`, `VideoStreamProfile` and so on. Therefore to align with the rest of the design, a separate class for AdvancedMode is probably preferred, which tries to `rs2_is_device_extendable_to(dev, RS2_EXTENSION_ADVANCED_MODE)` to allow the cast. What do you think?
",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
