16461,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-16 08:57:06+00:00,91379993,tensorflow/tensorboard,4317806,wchargin,15658638,tensorflow,297575985,366178025,"I fully agree with both of @nfelt's comments, especially: that the API should not have a single `histogram` function that does two things, and that in the case of nonlinear bins the frontend should be updated accordingly.

> The frontend's re-distribution of frequencies might sort of accidentally accommodate this but it also might not (I haven't tried it) 

It should get it approximately correct, yes ([relevant source here](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/dad4df940deaf5b94751c125aeea1cee56c67522/tensorboard/plugins/histogram/tf_histogram_dashboard/histogramCore.ts#L107-L110)); there will be artifacts at the edges of a really wide bin. It should indeed be refined.

> For getting this to work urgently, I think you ought to be able to basically just run the op code you wrote directly - i.e. it would boil down to calling `tf.summary.tensor_summary()` explicitly with your tensor of edges and bucket counts, and attaching a `SummaryMetadata` from `tensorboard.plugins.histogram.metadata`.  It's going ""under the hood"" a little but that should at least get you unblocked, unless I'm mistaken?

The only problem with this is that [the build target for the `metadata` module is `//tensorboard:internal`](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/blob/dad4df940deaf5b94751c125aeea1cee56c67522/tensorboard/plugins/histogram/BUILD#L47-L58), so it's directly accessible from a Bazel project. But if you are using TensorBoard as a pypi package, then the following (untested) should be all you need:
```py
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorboard.plugins.histogram import metadata as histogram_metadata


def pre_computed_histogram_op(bin_edges, weights):
  summary_metadata = histogram_metadata.create_summary_metadata(...)
  with tf.name_scope(...):
    bin_edges = tf.cast(bin_edges, tf.float64)
    weights = tf.cast(data, tf.float64)
    tensor = tf.transpose(tf.stack([bin_edges[:-1], bin_edges[1:], weights]))
    return tf.summary.tensor_summary(
        name='histogram_summary',
        tensor=tensor,
        collections=None,
        summary_metadata=summary_metadata)
```
(If you want direct `pb` output, similarly adapt the `pb` code in `summary.py`.)",{},MEMBER,User,False
