16479,IssueCommentEvent,2018-04-24 23:02:58+00:00,91379993,tensorflow/tensorboard,710113,nfelt,15658638,tensorflow,236572522,384106862,"It was pointed out that #938 is a duplicate of this older issue.  There's some valuable more recent discussion on #938 but we're centralizing on this issue for tracking purposes.

I've marked this contributions welcome, since we are stretched thin in terms of our ability to do new feature work right now.  That said, I agree that this should be fixed and we would happily take a PR to replace the ModifiedLog scale with a true log scale as long as it has some reasonable provision for negative values (like the matplotlib style here: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorboard/issues/938#issuecomment-367865761).",{},COLLABORATOR,User,False
16485,IssueCommentEvent,2017-11-01 18:07:46+00:00,91379993,tensorflow/tensorboard,49262,jart,15658638,tensorflow,266536167,341190817,Thank you @caisq.,{},MEMBER,User,False
16489,IssueCommentEvent,2018-01-30 19:26:29+00:00,91379993,tensorflow/tensorboard,8533952,fortran-favors-the-old,15658638,tensorflow,292172148,361706010,"Hey @nfelt , thanks for looking at this.

I won’t have access to my computer until the end of the day, so I’ll show you the output I get from running your suggested command later.

That said, I’m not surprised by your output above. That wheel has `Requires-Python` metadata correctly populated, which pip is picking up on in your case (and perhaps mine too; I’m guessing I would have seen that too if I had passed verbose flags like you).

I suspect that in your case, assuming `futures` installation eventually succeeds for you, that pip eventually tries to install the 3.1.1 sdist and succeeds, since 3.1.1 is compatible with Python 3.

In my case, for whatever reason, pip eventually attempts to install 3.2.0 sdist (since there’s no 3.2.0 Python 3 wheel to attempt first). Since it’s an sdist, pip can’t see any `Python-Requires` metadata ahead of time, so it attempts installation from the sdist, which eventually fails due to blacklisting Python 3 in setup.py . When package installation fails at this point, pip errors out.

When I observed this inconsistency in which package versions are attempted is when I really started really scratching my head when making my initial report. I probably should have mentioned back then what I’m about to say now, but I didn’t want to overload you with information.

[PEP 440]() has this IMO unfortunate line:

```
When multiple candidate versions match a version specifier, the preferred version SHOULD be the latest version as determined by the consistent ordering defined by the standard Version scheme.
```

",{},NONE,User,False
