16573,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-05 06:34:20+00:00,55808787,openthread/openthread,14219401,erja-gp,16142269,openthread,257310552,334371862,"Correct. But this should exactly match with the retransmitted frames.
Typically you will have (received by the 'slow' joiner from the commissioner):
- hello verify request -> seq 0
- server hello, server key exchange, server Hello Done -> dtls seq 1,2,3
then the retransmit which we want to ignore (as we have been busy with the previous key exchange):
- server hello, server key exchange, server Hello Done -> dtls seq 4,5,6

So by not retransmitting below 6, you would not reply to the last message.
The idea is that you know how long it takes to perform the crypto calculations, and therefor you know exactly how many duplicates (and dtls seq numbers) you will receive, and how many you need to ignore.

If the crypto calculations take > 8s, you expect 1 retransmit, so don't reply untill dtls seq > 6.
If the crypto calculations take > 24s, you expect 2 retransmits, so don't reply untill dtls seq > 9.
etc...
The number '6' is thus not an absolute constant, but something which needs to be adapted depending on the speed of the specific platform.

If your comment is about retransmitting the 'Hello request' in case we missed the 'Hello Verify Request', I have to admit it did not take that into account. Perhaps we should use two limits and ignore only dtls sequence numbers >3 and <=6. But I would need to check the code to see if that scenario passes via the same if statement.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
