16934,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-31 13:24:42+00:00,31667038,latchset/jwcrypto,8332609,simo5,17146082,latchset,174170925,243762543,"We can't remove all timing variations but that is not the point, we just need to avoid big enough variations to be measurable over the network. Different messages already cause different timings on their own.
It makes no sense to remove RSA1_5 because we have a mitigation and the vulnerability is usage specific, it is only present if an attacker can capture messages and use a server as an oracle. There are perfectly valid uses of this algorithm and it is mandated by the standard,",{},,User,False
16937,IssueCommentEvent,2018-02-20 03:15:28+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,2812720,tleonhardt,17161025,python-cmd2,298145163,366855794,"That function is already hijacking ``self.stdout`` and redirecting it to a file.  I'd have to look at it - we might be able to hijack ``sys.stdout`` and also redirect it to that file.  But in order to get all of the features of ``cmd2`` to work properly, such as redirecting command output to a file and the ability to pipe command output to a shell command, it is important to use ``self.poutput()`` or ``self.stdout.write()``.  If your end users are POSIX-shell savvy, then those are really killer features.  I can't tell you how many times the ability to pipe command output to **grep** has just rocked socks.

At the very least I will keep this issue open and try to improve the documentation to let users know they should be using ``poutput()``.

@kotfu and I have been busy lately!  ;-)  We managed to get a bunch of good features into the 0.8 release.  I've gotten a lot of positive feedback about the new argparse decorators and I love how they open up the ability to support sub-commands.  We also have some really cool stuff coming up in the 0.8.1 release - in particular the ability to have sub-menus and persistent readline history.  Your thanks is appreciated and we are glad you like it.",{},CONTRIBUTOR,User,False
