17025,IssueCommentEvent,2017-04-28 01:31:07+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4459524,jagerman,17565521,pybind,224929301,297883318,"The error isn't all that surprising: it isn't valid to dereference a `shared_ptr<void>`.  In order for it to become useful (or even usable) in C++ you need to `std::{static,dynamic,reinterpret}_pointer_cast` it to some type based on some external type information.  Even though pybind can, technically, bind a `void *`-returning function, it doesn't do anything particularly useful: it just becomes `None`.  It does that mainly to support casting a `void` function (rather than a `void *`) because it avoids needing to add special case for `void` functions.

The pybind behaviour of allowing binding a `void *` function is sort of accidental: a `void *` or a `shared_ptr<void>` is really something fundamentally different: it's a pointer to an unknown type which is really only useful when combined with the type via some other means.  But for a `void *` or `shared_ptr`-equivalent, pybind doesn't have the type, so there's really no way that this can be meaningfully returned to Python.  At best you'd get a `None` in Python, but it actually seems better to me to just not allow that--and, in fact, to even disallow binding a function that returns a `void *`.  Not because it wouldn't be useful, but because there's no way to get the type out of it, and without the type there's no way to do anything with it.",{},,User,False
