17039,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-08 15:07:54+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,21983492,po2xel,17565521,pybind,175737141,245629281,"Hi Wenzel,

I reviewed your fix. But I am afraid it may be a little quick and dirty. 
I tried this solution before I sent my pull request. It works, but it is error prone. Not everyone knows that they should call `inc_ref` when they need a **none** object. It is indeed an implementation detail and should not be exported. And, I think that is one of the many reasons why Python objects' reference counts are managed by c++ class in pybind11.

By the way, Py_None is a special and unique Python object. It is much more efficient to manage it as a global object.

Please let me if I misunderstand your design.

It is my honor to share my thought with you.

Best Regards,
Po",{},,User,False
17041,IssueCommentEvent,2017-05-03 10:10:10+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4831417,dean0x7d,17565521,pybind,219731426,298871444,"If adding methods to `enum_` is a desirable feature, I'd suggest making that official and documented first (preferably in a separate PR for clarity). I feel like the current undocumented way of adding methods is unfortunate because of the broken chaining. Making it explicit and documented would be nice. Something like:

```c++
py::enum_<Foo>(m, ""Foo"")
    .value(""First"", Foo::First)
    .value(""Second"", Foo::Second)
    .classify() // `class_` functions permitted after this point; no more `enum_`
    .def(""__str__"", [](Foo const&) { ... });
```

The `enum_` implementation in this case would go from:
```c++
class enum_ : public class_ { ... };
```
to:
```c++
class enum_ {
public:
    class_& clasify() { return cls; }

private:
    class_ cls;
};
```

Using composition here instead of inheritance would simplify things overall since there would be no need for CRTP.",{},,User,False
