17192,IssueCommentEvent,2017-07-26 16:19:32+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,295816,erikrose,17889013,certbot,243222265,318105421,"@bmw I'm having trouble reproducing it reliably. I got it the first time, but now it just works quietly:

    [10:42:20]% virtualenv --no-site-packages --setuptools venv2
    New python executable in /Users/erose/Desktop/venv2/bin/python2.7
    Also creating executable in /Users/erose/Desktop/venv2/bin/python
    Installing setuptools, pip, wheel...done.% ./venv2/bin/pip install pip==9.0.1
    ./venv2/bin/pip install setuptools==36.2.0
    Collecting pip==9.0.1
      Using cached pip-9.0.1-py2.py3-none-any.whl
    Installing collected packages: pip
      Found existing installation: pip 8.0.2
        Uninstalling pip-8.0.2:
          Successfully uninstalled pip-8.0.2
    Successfully installed pip-9.0.1
    Collecting setuptools==36.2.0
      Using cached setuptools-36.2.0-py2.py3-none-any.whl
    Installing collected packages: setuptools
      Found existing installation: setuptools 19.6.1
        Uninstalling setuptools-19.6.1:
          Successfully uninstalled setuptools-19.6.1
    Successfully installed setuptools-36.2.0
    [12:11:49]% sudo ./venv2/bin/python /Users/erose/Checkouts/pipstrap/pipstrap.py
    Password:
    [12:12:13]%

It's not a bug in pip or pipstrap; pip is just trying to dodge a privilege escalation, and pipstrap does nothing but call pip. However, I think we could work around it in pipstrap by passing --no-cache-dir to pip.

Could somebody who can reproduce this reliably try adding --no-cache-dir to their pipstrap (just search for ""pip install"")?",{},,User,False
