17198,IssueCommentEvent,2016-08-02 16:43:23+00:00,26516210,certbot/certbot,1750103,schoen,17889013,certbot,168908299,236965051,"Hi,

This would be more suitable to discuss at the Let's Encrypt Community Forum. There are two existing threads related to the desire for a higher SSL Labs score with Nginx and Apache:

https://community.letsencrypt.org/t/how-to-get-an-a-rating-on-qualys-ssl-labs-with-nginx-without-breaking-loads-of-browsers/4582

https://community.letsencrypt.org/t/howto-a-with-all-100-s-on-ssl-labs-test-using-apache2-4-read-warnings/2436

You could also start a new thread there if neither of these is exactly relevant.

It's not surprising that the default configuration from Nginx or Certbot wouldn't give a 100% score because, as those threads discuss, getting a perfect score requires reducing browser compatibility to exclude browsers that only support older crypto mechanisms.

I don't believe that there is anything about the cert itself that is limiting your score, but you can discuss and clarify the details on the community forum.",{},,User,False
17201,IssueCommentEvent,2016-09-19 10:23:40+00:00,4198043,ArduPilot/MAVProxy,7077857,peterbarker,17919847,ArduPilot,154287785,247958157,"The chances of a corrupt packet getting through are pretty slim, considering MAVLink's own CRC.  However, the chances of them getting as far as MAVLink's decoding aren't that bad.  My short amount of reading shows Golay12 will detect up to 7 bits of error in 24.  Which is fine, but I can see a standard telemetry link having more corruption than that.

Turning ECC off on the telemetry radios is not uncommon.

What you're probably seeing here are the bytes which do *not* correspond to valid packets being spat out.  The option @SamuelDudley pointed you at stop these unrecognised bytes being spat out.

@AndKe Are you happy with that explanation?
",{},,User,False
