17315,IssueCommentEvent,2018-03-19 16:30:31+00:00,7673329,simple-salesforce/simple-salesforce,44789,candlerb,19581234,simple-salesforce,306486551,374275697,"A bit busy right now.  I am using this functionality as part of cleaning up in a test suite; not having it just means my test suite runs slightly slower than it could :-)

However there is a bigger question of how best to expose this in the Python API.  There is no use of [/compose/sobjects](https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.api_rest.meta/api_rest/resources_composite_sobjects_collections.htm) yet in simple-salesforce.

There are other useful composite calls there - in particular I like the look of [composite get](https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.api_rest.meta/api_rest/resources_composite_sobjects_collections_retrieve.htm) which allows you to retrieve just the fields of interest. I have been using SOQL queries to do this until now.

So maybe it should look similar to the bulk API, e.g.

~~~
sf.composite.Product2.get(ids, fields)
~~~

However the 'create', 'delete' and 'update' operations can work on mixed object types:

~~~
sf.composite.create(records, allOrNone=False)
sf.composite.update(records, allOrNone=False)
sf.composite.delete(ids, allOrNone=False)
