17491,IssueCommentEvent,2016-11-22 15:36:11+00:00,37137879,QCoDeS/Qcodes,10207298,damazter,20478252,QCoDeS,190763836,262273687,"@nataliejpg 
A quick response to your message above
It would be great if this Alazar driver gets extended to work with other alazar cards as well!
I  have not taken the time yet to read all the changes proposed here. (I would like to check the changes to ATS.py)

> I've written it such that the get_sample_rate function doesn't work for the ATS9360 and i'm not sure what the best way to implement this such that it works is (the issue is that the byte to value dict of the sampling rate should be different depending on the value of another parameter which sets how it works out the sample rate, not sure the 'nice' way to write this')

I am not sure that I know what you mean, but with the ATS 9870 you had to take the decimation into account which is done in the `get_sample_rate` function in `ats.py` does this solve your problem or would a similar approach solve your problem?

>how should different acq controllers be organised? all in one big file seems messy but also the way I've done it seems overkill, maybe just have two files in the master branch: the existing one by @damazter and one which works for the ATS9360 and returns an array

and

> currently the two acq controllers rec_samp and rec_buf don't work, they are designed to return a 2d dataset in one acquisition, I didnt try super hard to get them to work but also not sure why they don't, @alexcjohnson any ideas?

My original idea was to not put any acquisition controllers in qcodes as it might by to personal from person to person. But I had to put at least one their to sort of explain the idea of the driver (making sure that ATS_WORKS.ipnb works)
The reason that the example does not return an array is that qcodes loops do not play nicely with these kinds of array parameters yet, so I decided to have an example which is not hacky in any way, but would not be really useful as a practical acquisition_contoller. (It only saves a single point per acquisition which is not that useful).

",{},,User,False
