17914,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-06 01:04:08+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,7438501,Tobotimus,23690422,Cog-Creators,347738532,410562481,":+1: This is awesome! This is just a suggestion of mine that could cut down on lines used and perhaps increase usability and extensibility:
 - Simply have `ctx` as an attribute to the predicate since we might add more checks which need more context
 - Use classmethods to instantiate the `Predicate` object and return the requested function in one single expression.

Take your example in the header of this PR. With above suggestions implemented, it could look like this:
```py
from redbot.core import commands
from redbot.core.utils.predicates import Predicate

class CogExample:
    # setup code
    @commands.command()
    async def example(self, ctx):
        await ctx.send(""Please set a new welcome message."")
        
        try:
            welcome_message = await self.handler(ctx)
        except asycnio.TimeoutError:
            await ctx.send(""Response timed out."")
        except RuntimeError:
            await ctx.send(""Cancelled setting a new welcome message."")
        # rest of your code

    async def handler(self, ctx):
        message = await ctx.bot.wait_for('message', timeout=30, check=Predicate.length_under(ctx, length=2000))
        await ctx.send(""Are you sure you wish to change your message?"")
        choice = await ctx.bot.wait_for('message', timeout=30, check=Predicate.confirm(ctx))
        if choice.content.lower() in ('y', 'yes'):
            return message.content
        else:
            raise RuntimeError

```

The proposed classmethods could return the Predicate object itself but modify its `__call__` to match the requested predicate function.

Also I think most message predicates ought to check for `ctx.channel == m.channel`, otherwise the bot could unexpectedly pick up responses in other channels.

@calebj has some good suggestions too.

I really like this initiative! In fact I think (in another PR) we could add a `ReactionPredicate` to compliment this one. Perhaps in the interest of future-proofing the naming scheme, this could be renamed to `MessagePredicate`? Let me know if you have any qualms or queries.",{},MEMBER,User,False
17916,IssueCommentEvent,2017-10-20 03:38:25+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,3731082,tekulvw,23690422,Cog-Creators,266851525,338097614,That information would be good to add as well. I don't personally have anything else on my mind to add adn I think that after dpy/package information is in this PR we should go ahead and merge.,{},OWNER,User,False
17924,IssueCommentEvent,2018-08-19 07:08:31+00:00,48904888,Cog-Creators/Red-DiscordBot,7438501,Tobotimus,23690422,Cog-Creators,351818750,414108506,"After a bit of research and testing, I've decided against the proposition of using submodules. These are my reasons:
 - Cloning submodules includes *everything* which would be located in that submodule, as shown in the following image:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7438501/44306421-ec22dc00-a3d1-11e8-84eb-311186ee68f0.png)
    This means we'd have to be more specific in our globs for `package_data` in `setup.py` - part of this PR was to make that more general to simplify the process of adding data files in the future.
 - (the main reason) When the submodule is added and pushed to this main repo, it points to a specific commit on the submodule's repo, so if there any updates to the trivia lists we'd like to include in the next release, we'd have to open a new PR over here to update them. This is annoying and is a similar problem to the one we have now of maintaining separate release cycles on PyPI, and having to update the version pin on this repo every time Red-Trivia makes a new release.

So for those reasons I'm sticking to this approach here.",{},MEMBER,User,False
